  "chunk_index": 33,
  "summary": "After searching Sir Oswald's study, Jimmy Sycamore ensures the drawers are locked to avoid detection by the meticulous Rupert Bettman and exits the room. In the hallway, Jimmy encounters Bettman, who claims he was investigating a potential thief. Jimmy notices a bulge in Bettman's pocket, suggesting the man is carrying a gun, and mockingly refers to him as an \"ape.\" Jimmy uses the excuse that he was looking for cookies because a guest tin was empty, later revealing he has hidden a heap of unappetizing cookies in a dressing table drawer to eat later. Jimmy observes that Bettman is suspicious, appears to never sleep, and seems to be everywhere.\n\nLater, Eileen Bündel and Loire arrive at the house after their Sienna breaks down, successfully executing the plan Jimmy had previously proposed. They are greeted by Mrs. Cutt and join Terence O'Rourke and others for lunch. During the meal, Loire engages Bettman in conversation, praising his vast knowledge. Following lunch, the group plays a game of clockwork golf involving Bettman, Loire, O'Rourke, and Bündel; Bettman and Loire emerge as the winners. Jimmy joins the group, appearing confident, and offers to drive the women to the garage, complaining of indigestion from the cookies. Afterward, Bündel and Loire discuss their success in distracting Bettman and O'Rourke, while Jimmy remarks that while O'Rourke was easy to handle, Bettman is \"omnipresent.\"",
